<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">first off, for those observant people, yes that is the same dwarf half as in my new nazgul deck. i found it swaps into this deck well, and is 30 cards, so very little replacement (sites) is needed. <br>
<br>
so, bid 0, go second. the dwarves can hold their own, there&#39;s enough weapons to get them to gimli and fror (or farin if you think you&#39;re up against orcs) keep the dwarven bumps and hobbit stealths, but keep the hand space for the uruk surprise. <br>
<br>
free: the dwarves rumble on with all their gear, let the opponent stay in the lead (not too far though) and survive. weaknesses again are versus Nazgul, and swarms (and more i know) but they moving with gimli, frodo and fror is fairly cheap.<br>
<br>
<br>
shadow: i said that the deck is battle cry based, and then i remembered that i took one out and that worry seemed to work very well while i was concentrating on the cries. hence, go for the kills when you can, but let worry pile up the burdens, this balance seems to win skirmishes. the spies of saruman are best used for the guards, and lurtz with his sword and a cry is always fun to play. <br>
<br>
play a slow free peoples strat, and go for the uruk kill with the shadow  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
